<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-243-512  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 243 512.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  March 12 1990 v7 n11 p32(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Wading through the maze of user interfaces. (Wide-Area Networks)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kobielus, James.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The network interface information overload is a problem for userslooking for information.andP;  Sometimes, users need to run throughmore than a half-dozen on-line system environments, includingoperating systems, local-area network operating systems,communications software packages and more when looking for asingle bit of information.andP;  Developers must offer users easyaccess to information in a familiar format.andP;  The many differentsystems environments must be integrated into a single look andfeel.andP;  Traveling from one different system to another must be doneautomatically and without the user being aware of the transition.andO;IBM's Systems Application Architecture is a good attempt atproviding users with a unified environment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     NetworksUser InterfaceInformation Resources ManagementUser NeedsOperating Environments.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>